VALUES
(42, 19, 12, 43, 18, 37, 37, 'a certain nobleman went into a far country', 'Kingship and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of kingship, as both passages reference a nobleman or king. The nobleman in Luke goes to receive a kingdom, while Jesus acknowledges his kingship in John, indicating a shared focus on authority and the establishment of a kingdom.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 12, 58, 9, 28, 28, 'to receive for himself a kingdom', 'Return of the Nobleman and Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of a nobleman going to receive a kingdom and the anticipation of Christ''s return. Both passages emphasize a journey to establish authority and the expectation of a second coming.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 12, 60, 3, 22, 22, 'to receive for himself a kingdom', 'Nobleman and Kingdom Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of a nobleman going to receive a kingdom, paralleling the ascension of Christ to heaven to assume authority. Both passages emphasize the idea of a figure departing to gain a position of power and returning.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 12, 40, 21, 38, 38, NULL, 'Inheritance and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of inheritance and authority, as both passages involve a nobleman or son who is associated with a kingdom or estate. The nobleman''s journey to receive a kingdom in Luke parallels the husbandmen''s desire to seize the inheritance in Matthew.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 13, 40, 25, 14, 15, 'Occupy till I come', 'Servants and Stewardship', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of servants being entrusted with resources to manage during their master''s absence. The call to ''occupy till I come'' in Luke parallels the distribution of goods in Matthew, highlighting the expectation of faithful stewardship.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 13, 43, 12, 26, 26, 'Occupy till I come', 'Servanthood and Faithfulness', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of serving and following. In Luke, the servants are instructed to ''occupy'' until the master returns, while in John, serving Jesus is linked to being honored by the Father. This connection highlights the theme of faithful service.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 13, 46, 12, 7, 11, 'Occupy till I come', 'Stewardship of Gifts', 'This connection highlights the responsibility of believers to actively use their gifts and resources. Both passages emphasize the importance of being productive and faithful in service until the return of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 13, 60, 4, 9, 11, 'Occupy till I come', 'Stewardship and Service Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship in both passages. In Luke, the servants are instructed to ''Occupy till I come,'' reflecting the responsibility to manage what has been entrusted to them, while 1 Peter emphasizes being ''good stewards of the manifold grace of God'' in serving others.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 13, 45, 12, 6, 8, 'Occupy till I come', 'Servanthood and Responsibility', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship and the expectation of active engagement in one''s responsibilities. Both passages emphasize the importance of utilizing given gifts and resources until the return of the master.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 13, 46, 12, 28, 29, 'Occupy till I come', 'Servanthood and Responsibility', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship and responsibility in both passages. In Luke, the servants are instructed to ''Occupy till I come,'' while in 1 Corinthians, various roles in the church emphasize the responsibility of believers to serve in different capacities.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 13, 61, 1, 1, 1, 'servants', 'Servanthood and Faith Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of servants in their respective contexts. In Luke, the servants are entrusted with responsibilities, while in 2 Peter, Peter identifies himself as a servant of Christ, highlighting the importance of faith and duty.', 'theme', 0.349, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 14, 9, 8, 7, 7, 'We will not have this man to reign over us', 'Rejection of Authority Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of a ruler. In Luke, the citizens declare, ''We will not have this man to reign over us,'' paralleling the sentiment in 1 Samuel where the people reject God''s reign.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 14, 44, 7, 51, 52, 'We will not have this man to reign over us.', 'Rejection of Authority Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of authority. In Luke, the citizens refuse to have the man reign over them, while in Acts, the people resist the Holy Ghost, paralleling their ancestors'' rejection of prophets.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 14, 44, 3, 14, 15, 'We will not have this man to reign over us', 'Rejection of Authority', 'This connection highlights the rejection of rightful authority in both passages. In Luke 19:14, the citizens declare, ''We will not have this man to reign over us,'' paralleling the denial of Jesus as ''the Holy One'' in Acts 3:14-15.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 14, 19, 2, 1, 3, 'We will not have this man to reign over us', 'Rejection of Authority Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of authority. In Luke, the citizens declare, ''We will not have this man to reign over us,'' paralleling the rulers in Psalms who conspire against the Lord and His anointed.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 14, 42, 19, 27, 27, 'We will not have this man to reign over us.', 'Rejection of Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of the ruler. The citizens express their refusal to have him reign, and the enemies are punished for not wanting him to reign over them.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 14, 43, 15, 18, 18, 'hated him', 'Connection of Hatred and Rejection', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by leaders. Both passages emphasize the hatred directed towards those in authority, illustrating a common response from the world.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 14, 23, 49, 7, 7, 'We will not have this man to reign over us', 'Rejection of Leadership', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection of authority. Both passages emphasize the disdain shown towards a leader, with citizens in Luke declaring, ''We will not have this man to reign over us,'' and Isaiah referring to one whom ''man despiseth.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 15, 45, 14, 10, 12, 'that he might know how much', 'Judgment and Accountability Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of accountability before a ruler. Both passages emphasize the necessity of giving an account for one''s actions, whether to a master or to God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 15, 46, 4, 1, 5, NULL, 'Stewardship and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship and accountability in both passages. In Luke 19:15, the servants are called to account for their trading, while in 1 Corinthians 4:1-5, Paul emphasizes the requirement for stewards to be found faithful and the eventual judgment by the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 15, 19, 2, 4, 6, 'having received the kingdom', 'Kingship and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of kingship and the accountability of servants. In both passages, there is an emphasis on a ruler''s authority and the expectation of response from those under that authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 15, 40, 18, 23, 35, NULL, 'Account of Servants', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of taking account of servants and their actions. In Luke, the master calls his servants to account for their trading, while in Matthew, the king reckons with his servants regarding their debts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 15, 40, 25, 19, 19, NULL, 'Servants'' Accountability Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the accountability of servants to their lord upon his return. They highlight the expectation of reckoning for the gains made during his absence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 15, 42, 12, 48, 48, NULL, 'Responsibility for Given Resources', 'Both passages emphasize the expectation of accountability for what has been entrusted. In Luke 19:15, the servants are called to report on their trading, while Luke 12:48 highlights that much is required from those to whom much has been given.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 15, 42, 16, 2, 13, NULL, 'Stewardship and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship and the necessity of giving an account for one''s management of resources. Both passages emphasize the importance of being faithful in one''s responsibilities, as seen in the steward''s actions in Luke 16:2-13 and the servants'' accountability in Luke 19:15.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 16, 46, 15, 10, 10, NULL, 'Grace and Labor Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of laboring for results through grace. In both passages, the emphasis is on the outcomes of one''s efforts, whether it be gaining ten pounds or laboring abundantly by grace.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 16, 55, 4, 7, 8, NULL, 'Faithfulness and Reward', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of faithfulness and the rewards that follow. In Luke, the servant''s gain reflects diligence, while in 2 Timothy, the crown of righteousness signifies the reward for keeping the faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 16, 59, 2, 18, 26, 'thy pound hath gained ten pounds', 'Faith and Works Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of accountability in both passages. In Luke, the servant''s productivity with the pound reflects the necessity of works, paralleling James'' assertion that faith is demonstrated through actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 16, 13, 29, 14, 16, 'thy pound hath gained ten pounds', 'Stewardship and Divine Ownership', 'This connection highlights the theme of stewardship, where the servant in Luke acknowledges the increase of the pound given by the Lord, paralleling the acknowledgment in Chronicles that all offerings come from God. Both passages emphasize the idea that what is given back to God originates from Him.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 19, 16, 51, 1, 28, 29, 'thy pound hath gained ten pounds', 'Faithful Stewardship and Labor', 'This connection highlights the theme of diligent effort in service. Both passages emphasize the importance of working to yield results, whether it be gaining ''ten pounds'' or striving to present ''every man perfect in Christ.''', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
